<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41837859</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>25</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>25</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1520-5118</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>74</Volume><Issue>11</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>25</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of agricultural and food chemistry</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Agric Food Chem</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Unlocking Enzyme Discovery: A High-Resolution Gene Cluster Database Powered by Phylogenetic Insights and Machine Learning.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>9485</StartPage><EndPage>9500</EndPage><MedlinePgn>9485-9500</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1021/acs.jafc.5c06841</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>High-throughput sequencing has generated vast genomic repositories that remain under-annotated, hampering enzyme discovery. We present an integrated pipeline that (i) builds a high-resolution, cross-kingdom phylogenetic database, (ii) mines candidates via multilocus phylogeny, (iii) predicts activities using an evolutionary-scale protein language model, and (iv) removes false positives through multilevel residue-atom contact rescoring. When applied to the r-BOX pathway, this approach uncovered numerous previously undocumented FadB, BktB, Ter, and YdiI homologues. Our activity model achieved <i>R</i><sup>2</sup> = 0.68 and reduced the RMSE on high-value targets by 11% compared to the prior SOTA (UniKP). Contact scoring improved early enrichment (EF1%) by 16-fold. Experimental validation targeting FadB increased titers from 0.65 g/L (shake flasks) to 1.7 g/L, reaching 10.2 g/L in a fermentation process. Together, these results establish a robust, generalizable framework for discovering scarce, high-value enzymes and prioritizing functional variants at scale.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Sidun</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, 1800 Lihu Road, Wuxi 214122, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>He</LastName><ForeName>Junlong</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, 1800 Lihu Road, Wuxi 214122, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Duan</LastName><ForeName>Xuguo</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-2136-0449</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Light Industry and Food Engineering, Nanjing Forestry University, Nanjing 210037, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Liu</LastName><ForeName>Zimin</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, 1800 Lihu Road, Wuxi 214122, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lan</LastName><ForeName>Zhouge</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, 1800 Lihu Road, Wuxi 214122, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Qiong</ForeName><Initials>Q</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The Key Laboratory of Industrial Biotechnology, Ministry of Education School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, Wuxi 214122, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Jianyang</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Yangzhong Jiaocheng Biotechnology Research Co., Ltd., 333 Gangmao Road,Yangzhong City 212200, Jiangsu Province, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo>